					<h4>Western Book Roundup</h4>
		
		<h1>High Plains Book Award Finalists Announced</h1>
		<h2><i></i></h2>
		<div class="text-feature_print">
							<p>By Jenny Shank, 6-16-10</p>
			
			
							<p>The Parmly Billings Library recently announced the finalists for the <a target="_blank" href="http://highplainsbookawards.org/" title="High Plains Book Awards">High Plains Book Awards</a> to honor &#8220;literary works which examine and reflect life on the High Plains.&#8221;  This year&#8217;s Emeritus Award will be presented to Margaret Coel, author of the Wind River mystery series.&nbsp; 
</p>
<p>
Several books featured by New West over the past year are among the finalists, including <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/an_interview_with_writer_pathologist_professor_and_rancher_robert_greer/C39/L39/" title="Robert Greer">Robert Greer</a>&#8216;s <I>Spoon</I> and Kent Meyers&#8217; <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/skin_and_bones_kent_meyers_twisted_tree/C39/L39/" title="Twisted Tree">Twisted Tree</a></I> in the Best Fiction category, <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/ted_koosers_short_sweet_summer_reminiscence/C39/L39/" title="Lights on a Ground of Darkness">Lights on a Ground of Darkness</a></I> by Ted Kooser in the Nonfiction category, <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/two_poems_from_holding_everything_down_by_william_notter/C39/L39/" title="Holding Everything Down">Holding Everything Down</a></I> by William Notter in the Poetry category, <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/riverbend_gives_self_published_novel_a_second_chance/C39/L39/" title="600 Hours of Edward">600 Hours of Edward</a></I> by Craig Lancaster and <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/from_missouri_to_montana_on_foot/C39/L39/" title="Seldom Seen: A Journey into the Great Plains">Seldom Seen: A Journey into the Great Plains</a></I> by Patrick Dobson in the Best First Book category, and <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/new_books_feature_western_quilters/C39/L39/" title="Border to Border: Historic Quilts and Quiltmakers of Montana">Border to Border: Historic Quilts and Quiltmakers of Montana</a></I> by Annie Hanshew and <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/little_house_on_the_prairie_with_septic_tank_troubles/C39/L39/" title="No Place Like Home">No Place Like Home</a></I> by Linda Hasselstrom in the Zonta Best Woman Writer category.
</p>
<p>
The complete list of finalists on the <a target="_blank" href="http://highplainsbookawards.org/" title="High Plains Book Awards">High Plains Book Awards</a> website.&nbsp; The winners will be announced at the October 8 Awards Banquet.
</p>
<p>
&#8226; Speaking of awards, Doug Rhinehart&#8217;s <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/color_contrast_desert_photography_by_doug_rhinehart_and_jon_ortner/C39/L39/" title="Desert Adagio">Desert Adagio</a></I>, one of the photography books I discussed last week, was a finalist for this year&#8217;s <a target="_blank" href="http://www.indiebookawards.com/2010_winners_and_finalists.php" title="Indie Book Awards">Indie Book Awards</a>.
</p>
<p>
Apart from these awards, this week&#8217;s news consists of several literary events around the region in the upcoming week:
</p>
<p>
<b>Arizona</b>
</p>
<p>
&#8226; Throughout this year, <a target="_blank" href="http://www.prescottlibrary.info/" title="Prescott Public Library">Prescott Public Library</a> in Arizona is hosting a series of presentations entitled &#8221;<a target="_blank" href="http://prescottdailycourier.com/main.asp?SectionID=1&amp;SubSectionID=1&amp;ArticleID=81405" title="Mexico: Prescott's Distant Neighbor">Mexico: Prescott&#8217;s Distant Neighbor</a>.&#8221;  The next speaker, on June 22, is author <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/revenge_of_the_saguaro_revels_in_southwest_tackiness/C39/L39/" title="Tom Miller">Tom Miller</a>, who will lead the audience on a &#8220;romp through borderland writing&#8221; beginning at 6:30 p.m.&nbsp; Miller will discuss examples from his <I>Writing on the Edge: A Borderlands Reader</I>, an anthology of writing about the U.S.-Mexico border from the 20th century.
</p>
<p>
<b>Colorado</b>
</p>
<p>
&#8226; Western State College in Gunnison, Colo., established a low-residency MFA program in writing this year, with concentrations in mainstream and genre fiction, poetry, and screenwriting.&nbsp; The writing program will sponsor this year&#8217;s <a target="_blank" href="http://www.western.edu/writingtherockies" title="Writing the Rockies conference">Writing the Rockies conference</a> from July 22 through 25.&nbsp; Keynote speakers include Mayank Gupta (screenwriting), Karla Kuban (fiction), and David Mason (poetry).
</p>
<p>
<b>Montana</b>
</p>
<p>
&#8226; <a target="_blank" href="http://www.whitefishreview.org/" title="Whitefish Review">Whitefish Review</a> will celebrate the release of its summer issue on June 24 with a reading by Montana&#8217;s Laura Munson, author of the New York Times Bestseller <I>This is Not the Story You Think It Is: A Season of Unlikely Happiness</i> (The Lodge at Whitefish Lake, 7-11 p.m.).&nbsp; The new issue features an interview with John Irving, and a conversation between Rick Bass and Doug Peacock.
</p>
<p>
<b>Utah</b>
</p>
<p>
&#8226; Ann Torrence will give a slideshow presentation of her book <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/two_new_travel_books_depict_the_west_from_distinct_vantages/C39/L39/" title="U.S. Highway 89: the Scenic Route to Seven Western National Parks">U.S. Highway 89: the Scenic Route to Seven Western National Parks</a></I> (which I reviewed for New West a few months ago) at <a target="_blank" href="http://www.anntorrence.com/blog/2010/06/thursday-booksigning-at-kings.html" title="King's English Books in Salt Lake City">King&#8217;s English Books in Salt Lake City</a> on Thursday, June 17 at 7 p.m.
</p>
<p>
